ce:section.ce:para:
The in vitro cytotoxicity effect of CQDs was analysed and investigated using the MTT assay to evaluate the applicability of carbon nanomaterials and confirm their nontoxicity due to their intrinsic carbon nature. The CC50 shows that the 50% concentration of the CQDs that caused the death of cells is 12% (Fig. 7
                     ). According to Table 2
                     , an OD value of >0.5 shows that the cell remains alive after treatment with CQDs. The cell viability of CQDs for all concentrations indicates that CQDs do not show significant toxicity to living cells. Moreover, CQDs can be tolerated at high concentration and long incubation time. Therefore, CQDs is suitable to be used for vivo and vitro applications. Wang et al. [12] reported that CQDs exhibit dose-dependent cytotoxicity with 70% of cell surviving at a concentration of 0.2 mg/mL, indicating that CQDs have low toxicity. Results indicate that CQDs derived from oil palm biomass are nontoxic quantum dots to cells even at high concentration.
